reviewText: Billy Crystal is a comic genious,and "Analyze This" is hysterically funny! This is a 2-sided (Non-Blu-Ray) DVD ("Analyze This" (side one) and "Analyze That" (side two)).I mention here that, as of this date (9-30-11), I have only watched "Analyze This". So that's the side of the DVD I'll review here.The sound and picture quality are first-rate. I watched it on a Sony Blu-Ray player and Sony 40" flatscreen TV (with 1080p capability). I also mention that the seller provided first quality service and the DVD arrived quickly in perfect condition. Good extras...especially the easy to navigate menu (with sound)featuring the trailer and scene selection (You'll want to replay the big "meeting" scene near the end of the movie multiple times! It's that funny!).Now,about the film "Analyze This", just in case you have not seen it. DeNiro and Crystal are absolutely magnificent together, Crystal as a psychiatrist who,through a quirk of fate, inherits mob-boss DeNiro as his patient. Hilarious stuff! No wonder there HAD to be a sequel. And let's not forget the rest of the ensemble--everyone is first-rate,including Lisa Kudrow,as Crystal's fiancee...so quirky and realistically annoying that one hopes the on-screen marriage never occurs!(For Billy's own good!).Oustanding script and direction...the movie flies by and you'll wish it was longer! I need to say that the big "meeting scene" near the end of the film is laugh out loud funny,replay it multiple times funny, and even laugh the next day funny! Billy Crystal is THE BEST...Wait until you hear his spiel at the mob meeting...you'll be in tears of laughter!I purchased this DVD on the strength of having seen it on broadcast TV,and enjoying it so much. I do need to mention that I had to deduct 1 star because the "R" rating is well-earned here. Unfiltered by network TV, be ready for: A few sexual situations and some moderate violence, but the language is really coarse. Lots of F-bombs, etc.. If I could have the ability to filter that out ("Analyze THAT"???)...or at least tone it down some, I'd do it. Having said that, one might argue that the language was necessary to add the realism of the subject matter and the "streets". Perhaps...but this mars an otherwise 7-star effort.There are no perfect movies out there...no perfect roses. HOWEVER, if one is able to look beyond the rugged language, which I would call the "thorns" of "Analyze This", one finds a BOUQUET of ROSES...a masterpiece of comedy. In this day and age, I think we all need a good laugh. And "Analyze This" delivers a huge helping of belly laughs! On a final note, I don't want to spoil the surprise, but amongst the wonderful music soundtrack of "Analyze This", look for a surprise and cool cameo by the great Tony Bennett. You'll love that extra treat!I look forward to viewing side 2 of this DVD soon. If "Analyze That" is even half as good as "Analyze This", it'll be a fun ride!
Title: Analyze This / Analyze That

reviewText: As an avid viewer of the gangster genre, I went into this one with high hopes...and wasn't disappointed. This film paints mobsters in the same sympathetic light that the original Godfather does (not the other ones, of course). DeNiro reenacts his famous heavy-handed mobster role with a whole new perspective in this very entertaining comedy. His off the wall character of a mob boss who breaks into tears at random intervals is priceless. Crystal works as the perfect dichotomy as the nervous psychologist who winds up over his head before he knows what has hit him. This film, although nothing past a simple comedy, is terrifically written and has more than it's fair share of laughs. Watch it. Have fun.
summary: If you know your mob flicks
Title: Analyze This / Analyze That

reviewText: Analyze This and and Analyze That have two terrific stars - Billy Crystal, a natural comic, and Robert DeNiro, a brilliant actor, who is as adept at comedy as he is at anything else he portrays.  Of course in both films DeNiro's comedy is played from the mouth of a tough guy mafioso, which he seems, like James Cagney of another movie era, to do best.  "...This" has very funny moments all based on the fact that a genunine murdering fiend is suffering from having lost his father, and is no longer an effective killer.  Billy Crystal, a psychiatrist, about to be married for a second time, is pressed into duty, by the mobster.  By movie's end progress is made, and DeNiro reforms as he quits the mob and marches off to jail while singing Crystal's praises.The second film is simply terrific acting by the stars, who play their roles in a contrived story, and therein lies the problem of the second film.  Chas Palminteri is as good as DeNiro in his tough guy role.  All in all, it's fun entertainment based on an immoral premise.  "...This" is very funny; "...That" we can do without!
summary: Some Funny Stuff and Somewhat Less Funny Stuff
Title: Analyze This / Analyze That

reviewText: "You, you're good, you." Yes! Paul Vitti (Robert De Niro) is brilliant as the mobster who cries and gives no mercy to his enemies. Ben Sobel (Billy Crystal) becomes his shrink after one threat and there goes on! "Analyze This" is funny with Sobel trying to get married, but Vitti interrupts his life and shoots pillows for no reason. "Analyze That" is funnier with hilarious parts including the woman and the midget picture, the tuna casserole, and the "West Side Story" sing-a-longs. Momentous! These are two funny movies that people need to see.
Title: Analyze This / Analyze That

reviewText: I think more blu-rays should come in the cheaper double feature format. "Analyze This" is the best thing Billy Crystal has done -- he plays a jaded, milquetoast analyst living in his father's shadow, suddenly thrown into the world of the mob, while trying to start a new life with a new wife.  "Analyze That" continues when mobster-patient De Niro is released from prison in Crystal's FBI-imposed custody. What? A lot more talky than the faster, tenser, and funnier predecessor -- and no Chazz Palminteri. But it's not without its moments, namely De Niro's dream image of Crystal as a snorting Sigmund Freud, and outtakes during the closing credits.
Title: Analyze This / Analyze That
